# How to Build a Cash Flow Forecast Like a CFO (Step-by-Step)  
_By Arron Bennett ‚Ä¢ Strategic CFO ‚Ä¢ Founder, Bennett Financials_  
üìÖ **September 10, 2025**

> [üîó Read this article on BennettFinancials.com](https://bennettfinancials.com/how-to-build-a-cash-flow-forecast-like-a-cfo-step-by-step/)

---

## Introduction  
A cash flow forecast gives your business a clear view of when money will come in and when expenses will go out ‚Äî it‚Äôs a critical tool in keeping your business afloat. Despite its importance, many entrepreneurs feel intimidated because it seems technical and complicated.  
This guide walks you through the exact steps a CFO uses to build a clear, accurate forecast you can actually put into practice. :contentReference[oaicite:3]{index=3}

---

## Step-by-Step Process to Build a Cash Flow Forecast  
Here‚Äôs the practical eight-step method to build your forecast: :contentReference[oaicite:4]{index=4}

1. **Establish Your Forecasting Period and Frequency**  
   Decide how far ahead to forecast and how often to update. A 13-week rolling forecast updated weekly is often ideal. :contentReference[oaicite:5]{index=5}

2. **Gather Your Historical Cash Flow Data**  
   Pull in at least the past 12 months of cash movements to spot patterns in collections, payments and cycles. :contentReference[oaicite:6]{index=6}

3. **Map Your Cash Inflows**  
   Categorize all cash receipts‚Äîcustomer payments, loan proceeds, etc.‚Äîand model when the cash hits your bank based on realistic timing. :contentReference[oaicite:7]{index=7}

4. **Detail Your Cash Outflows**  
   List every cash payment: payroll, rent, suppliers, one-time cap-ex, tax bills‚Äîand pay close attention to *when* each payment happens. :contentReference[oaicite:8]{index=8}

5. **Calculate Your Net Cash Flow**  
   For each period, subtract total outflows from total inflows to determine net cash flow‚Äîpositive or negative. :contentReference[oaicite:9]{index=9}

6. **Determine Your Running Cash Balance**  
   Starting from current cash, add/subtract each period‚Äôs net cash flow to project your ending balance and track when you may run low. :contentReference[oaicite:10]{index=10}

7. **Driver-Based Forecasting & Scenario Modeling**  
   Use operational drivers (new customers, average deal size, collection days) for accuracy. Build ‚Äúwhat-if‚Äù scenarios to test risks and opportunities. :contentReference[oaicite:11]{index=11}

8. **Variance Analysis & Regular Updates**  
   Weekly or ongoing review of actual vs. forecasted cash flow helps refine your model, spot problem areas, and improve precision. :contentReference[oaicite:12]{index=12}

---

## Why This Matters  
- Helps you **anticipate cash shortfalls** instead of being surprised.  
- Gives you **clarity for growth decisions**, hiring, investments, or expansions.  
- Builds credibility with investors, lenders and stakeholders when you show disciplined cash management.

---

## Pro Tips for Implementation  
- Keep the model **simple enough** to maintain‚Äîtoo complex means you‚Äôll abandon it.  
- Update the forecast **regularly** and tie it into your leadership rhythm (weekly reviews work best).  
- Use the forecast as a **decision-support tool**, not just a spreadsheet exercise: ask ‚Äúwhat happens if?‚Äù before making big moves.

